  </solution>
  <exercise>
    <statement>
      <p>
        For each of the following functions, prove or
        disprove that the function is (i) a homomorphism; (ii)
        an isomorphism. (Remember to work with the default operation on each of these groups!)
        <ol>
          <li>
            <p>
              The function <m>f:\Z\to\Z</m> defined by <m>f(n)=2n</m>.
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
              The function <m>g:\R\to\R</m> defined by <m>g(x)=x^2</m>.
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
              The function <m>h:\Q^*\to\Q^*</m> defined by
              <m>h(x)=x^2</m>.
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </statement>
  </exercise>
  <solution>
    <title>print=false</title>
    <ol>
    <li>
      <ol>
        <li>
          <p>
            The function <m>f</m> is a homomorphism, since for every <m>a,b \in
            \Z,</m> we have
            <me>
              f(a+b)=2(a+b)=2a+2b=f(a)+f(b).
            </me>
          </p>
        </li>

        <li>
          <p>
            The function <m>f</m> isn't a bijection, since it isn't onto: for instance, there is
            no element <m>a</m> in <m>\Z</m> such that <m>f(a)=3</m>. Thus, <m>f</m> is not an
            isomorphism.
          </p>
        </li>
      </ol>
    </li>

    <li>
      <ol>
        <li>
          <p>
            The function <m>g</m> isn't a homomorphism: for instance, we have
            <me>
              g(2+3)=g(5)=25\neq 13=4+9=g(2)+g(3).
            </me>
          </p>
        </li>

        <li>
          <p>
            Since it isn't a homomorphism, it isn't an isomorphism.
          </p>
        </li>
      </ol>
    </li>

    <li>
      <ol>
        <li>
          <p>
            The function <m>h</m> is a homomorphism, since for every <m>a,b \in
            \Q,</m> we have
            <me>
              h(ab)=(ab)^2=a^2b^2=h(a)h(b).
            </me>
          </p>
        </li>

        <li>
          <p>
            The function <m>h</m> isn't onto: its range is the set of nonnegative rational
            numbers, not all of <m>\Q</m>. Thus, <m>h</m> is not an isomorphism.
          </p>
        </li>
      </ol>
    </li>
    </ol>
  </solution>
  <exercise>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Define <m>d : GL(n,\R)\to \R^*</m> by <m>d(A)=\det A</m>. Prove/disprove that <m>d</m> is:
        <ol>
          <li>
            <p>
              a homomorphism
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
              1-1
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
              onto
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
              an isomorphism.
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </statement>
  </exercise>
  <solution>
    <title>print=false</title>
    <ol>
      <li>
        <p>
          The function <m>d</m> is a homomorphism, since for every <m>A,B \in
          GL(n,\R),</m> we have
          <me>
            d(AB)=\det(AB)=(\det A)(\det B)=d(A)d(B).
          </me>
        </p>
      </li>

      <li>
        <p>
          <m>d</m> isn't 1-1: For instance, <m>d(I_2)=d(-I_2)</m>.
        </p>
      </li>

      <li>
        <p>
          <m>d</m> is onto: Let <m>a\in \R^*</m>. Then the matrix
          <me>
            A:=\begin{bmatrix}a \amp  0 \amp  0 \amp  \cdots \amp  0 \\
            0 \amp  1 \amp  0 \amp  \cdots \amp  0 \\
            0 \amp  0 \amp  1 \amp  \cdots \amp  0 \\
            \vdots \amp  \vdots \amp  \vdots \amp  \ddots \amp  \vdots \\
            0 \amp  0 \amp  0 \amp  \cdots \amp  1
            \end{bmatrix}
          </me>
          is in <m>GL(n,\R)</m>, with <m>d(A)=a</m>.
        </p>
      </li>

      <li>
        <p>
          Since <m>d</m> isn't 1-1, it isn't  an
          isomorphism.
        </p>
      </li>
    </ol>
  </solution>
  <exercise>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Complete the group tables for <m>\Z_4</m> and <m>\Z_8^{\times}</m>. Use the group tables to decide whether or not <m>\Z_4</m> and <m>\Z_8^{\times}</m> are isomorphic to one another. (You do not need to provide a proof.)
      </p>
    </statement>
  </exercise>
  <solution>
    <title>print=false</title>
    <p>
      The group tables of <m>\Z_4</m> and <m>\Z_8^{\times}</m> are, respectively,
      <me>
        \begin{array}{c||c|c|c|c}
        +\amp 0\amp 1\amp 2\amp 3\\ \hline\hline 0\amp 0\amp 1\amp 2\amp 3\\ \hline
        1\amp 1\amp 2\amp 3\amp 0\\ \hline 2\amp 2\amp 3\amp 0\amp 1\\ \hline 3\amp 3\amp 0\amp 1\amp 2
        \end{array}   \mbox{and}  
        \begin{array}{c||c|c|c|c}
        \cdot_8\amp 1\amp 3\amp 5\amp 7\\ \hline\hline 1\amp 1\amp 3\amp 5\amp 7\\ \hline 3\amp 3\amp 1\amp 7\amp 5\\
        \hline 5\amp 5\amp 7\amp 1\amp 3 \\ \hline 7\amp 7\amp 5\amp 3\amp 1
        \end{array} .
      </me>
    </p>

    <p>
      We can see from the group table for <m>\Z_8^{\times}</m> that every element of that group is its own inverse; that is not the case in <m>\Z_4</m>. Thus, <m>\Z_4\not\simeq\Z_8^{\times}</m>.
    </p>
  </solution>
  <exercise>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Let <m>n\in \Z^+</m>. Prove that <m>\langle n\Z,+\rangle  \simeq \langle \Z,+\rangle</m>.
      </p>
    </statement>
  </exercise>
  <solution>
    <title>print=false</title>
    <p>
      Define <m>\phi\,:\,\Z \rightarrow n\Z</m>
      by <m>\phi(x)=nx</m>, for all <m>x\in \Z</m>. Clearly, <m>\phi</m>
      is a bijection. Moreover, for all <m>x,y\in \Z</m>,
      <me>
        \phi(x+y)=n(x+y)=nx+ny=\phi(x)+\phi(y);
      </me>
      so <m>\phi</m> is a
      homomorphism. Thus, <m>\phi</m> is an isomorphism, and hence
      <me>
        \langle \Z, +\rangle \simeq \langle n\Z, +\rangle .
      </me>
    </p>
  </solution>
  <exercise>
    <statement>
      <ol>
        <li>
          <p>
            Let <m>G</m> and <m>G'</m> be groups, where <m>G</m> is abelian and  <m>G\simeq G'</m>. Prove that <m>G'</m> is abelian.
          </p>
        </li>

        <li>
          <p>
            Give an example of groups <m>G</m> and <m>G'</m>, where <m>G</m> is abelian and there exists a homomorphism from <m>G</m> to <m>G'</m>, but <m>G'</m> is NOT abelian.
          </p>
        </li>
      </ol>
    </statement>
  </exercise>
  <solution>
    <title>print=false</title>
    <ol>
      <li>
        <p>
          Since <m>G\simeq G'</m>, there exists some isomorphism <m>\phi:G\to G'</m>.  Let <m>x,y\in G'</m>.  Since <m>\phi</m> is onto, there exist <m>a,b\in G</m> such that <m>\phi(a)=x</m> and <m>\phi(b)=y</m>.  So
          <md>
            <mrow>xy\amp =\phi(a)\phi(b)\amp \amp</mrow>
            <mrow>\amp =\phi(ab)\amp \amp \text{ (since \(\phi\) is a homomorphism) }</mrow>
            <mrow>\amp =\phi(ba) \amp \amp \text{ (since \(G\) is abelian) }</mrow>
            <mrow>\amp =\phi(b)\phi(a)</mrow>
            <mrow>\amp =yx.</mrow>
          </md>
          Thus, <m>G'</m> is abelian.
        </p>
      </li>

      <li>
        <p>
          Let <m>G=\{I_2\}</m> (under multiplication) and let <m>G'=GL(2,\R)</m>. Then the map <m>\phi: G\to G'</m> defined by <m>\phi(I_2)=I_2</m> is clearly a homomorphism, but note that <m>G</m> is abelian while <m>G'</m> is not.
        </p>
      </li>
    </ol>
  </solution>
  <exercise>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Let <m>\langle G,\cdot\rangle</m> and <m>\langle G',\cdot'\rangle</m> be groups with identity elements <m>e</m> and <m>e'</m>, respectively, and let <m>\phi</m> be a homomorphism from <m>G</m> to <m>G'</m>. Let <m>a\in G</m>. Prove that <m>\phi(a)^{-1}=\phi(a^{-1})</m>.
      </p>
    </statement>
  </exercise>
  <solution>
    <title>print=false</title>
    <note>

    <p>
      We omit the group operations in this solution in order to increase familiarity with the convention.
    </p>

    </note>

    <p>
      We want to show that <m>\phi(a)^{-1}=\phi(a^{-1})</m>.
      Notice that
      <md>
        <mrow>\phi(a^{-1})\phi(a)\amp =\phi(a^{-1}a)\amp \amp \text{ (since \(\phi\) is a homomorphism) }</mrow>
        <mrow>\amp =\phi(e)\amp \amp \text{(by definition of \(a^{-1}\))}</mrow>
        <mrow>\amp =e'\amp \amp  \text{ (since \(\phi(e)\) is the identity element of
        \(G'\)) }</mrow>
        <mrow>\amp =\phi(a)^{-1}\phi(a)\amp \amp \text{(by definition of \(\phi(a)^{-1}\))} .</mrow>
      </md>
    </p>

    <p>
      Thus, <m>\phi(a^{-1})=\phi(a)^{-1}</m>, by right cancellation.
    </p>
  </solution>
